\section{Argument\label{argument}}

% strong state case
%\paragraph{Strong State Cases.} First, following the inertia of the colonial period, early independent Latin American states were governed by agricultural elites. Later, in the early 1900s, an incipient industrial sector was established. This sector was comprised of newcomers who were politically excluded. Second, in the strong state cases, industrial output rates were comparable to if not faster that agriculture growth rates. Third, the agricultural sector decelerated in the late 1900s. In order to sustain the economy, political elites could follow one of two strategies. They could either \emph{tax} or \emph{expropriate} industrial output. As industrial output was fast, the benefit of taxing a small sum of money ``today'' via taxation compensated for the long-term losses associated with having those resources ``tomorrow.'' Fourth, in exchange, the industrial class demanded commercial protectionism (tariffs) and political representation (early 20\emph{th}. century's oligarchies). Protectionist policies helped the industrial sector to develop further, generating an urban and educated middle class that grew under the eaves of the state. In turn, political representation broke the old political monopoly held by the agricultural sector, introducing the seed of early political competition.

% weak state case
%\paragraph{Weak State Cases.} Similarly, these nations were governed by agricultural monopolistic elites. However, in these cases agricultural incumbents faced slower industrial growth. This sector did not promise enough resources to tax. It was too costly to wait for for such a small tax revenue in the long run. In subsequent periods, firms could have gone bankrupt. Hence, agricultural incumbents were better off expropriating industries and politically blocking the industrial class. In these cases, the agricultural political monopoly was never challenged, the traditional economy was not broken and the endogenous incentives to invest in institutions designed to improve bureaucracies and split political power never existed. 

% the argument comes in four part
The argument comes in four parts: (1) the existence of an initial agricultural monopoly for all Latin American countries, (2) the emergence of a small industrial sector which developed at different rates, challenging (or not) the agricultural elites, (3) depending on the growth rate, the adoption of either expropriative or fiscal institutions, and (4) how the latter triggered the implementation of other state-institutions.

% (1) Latin American states were governed by agricultural monopolistic elites
\subsection{Agricultural Political Monopoly}

% monopoly: explaining in which sense this was a "monopoly".
Right after independence, the political system in Latin America was dominated by a compact social class invested in land.\footnote{\citet[280]{Johnston1966} argue that ``The development process begins with a situation in which the bulk of a country's population and economic activity is to be found in the agricultural sector. This is an historical fact, one of the most important `initial conditions' characterizing a nation's economy at an early stage of development.'' Similarly, \citet[59]{Kuznets1961a} argues that ``when modern economic growth begins, agriculture is the major sector in the economy. And by major I mean a dominant one.''} Agricultural elites controlling the economy also controlled the early post-colonial state, imposing social and economic policies favorable to them. Eventually, \emph{all} post-colonial nations saw the emergence of a small industrial sector, which grew at different rates (see \autoref{fig:incometax}). However, in countries that eventually turned into strong states, the size of the modern sector grew at faster rates.\footnote{It is important to say that the argument does not require European-like degrees of industrialization. As \citet[131]{Bertola2012} confirm, most Latin American countries did \emph{not} experience a proper industrialization \emph{process}, and hence it is inaccurate to say that the industrial sector ``had become a strong engine of economic growth.'' However, even though Latin America did not experience an industrial \emph{revolution}, the modern sector did develop in some countries (\autoref{fig:incometax}).} Because in these cases the industrial sector competed with the agricultural sector, agricultural elites tried first to block it, \emph{artificially} limiting political competition. However, for several reasons I explain later, inter-elite cooperation was incentive-compatible. On the contrary, where the size of the modern sector was small, agricultural elites were \emph{natural} monopolists. In these cases, there were not enough credible threats to landowners to seek a compromise between the two classes, which allowed the landowners to continue ruling without political opposition. This situation generated long-term political and economic distortions. 

% example paragraph
For example, early Nicaragua developed in a non-democratic context, just like every other country in the panel. However, its industrial sector did not grow fast enough to challenge the traditional sector (see \autoref{fig:incometax}), leaving the political system unaltered until the 1980s (see \autoref{fig:democracy:plot}). The lack of inter-elite contestation led this country to develop a fiscal system very late (vertical line in \autoref{fig:incometax}). The opposite happened in Ecuador, which passed the income tax just before the 1950s, right around when it had its first ``democratic'' experience. Below I will use the Chilean case to \hyperref[unpacking]{illustrate} the causal mechanisms at work in further detail explaining specifically how the initial monopolistic conditions were broken in the presence of a strong industrial sector and what the inter-elite compromises were. 

% (2) industrial output rates
\subsection{Industrial Output Speed Rates and Inter-Elite Contestation}

% explain the logic of industrial/agricultural output rates
There are many factors that explain industrial development in Latin America. Among them, tariffs oriented to protect the \emph{agricultural} market \emph{unintentionally} helped protect the industrial sector. Since the first industries processed raw agricultural materials, better conditions for the landowners helped the industrialists to make their way into the economy. Favorable international markets also boosted the demand for rudimentary processed raw products. I provide further details in my \hyperref[unpacking]{case study}. \autoref{fig:incometax} shows output differentials (in logarithmic scales) from 1900 to 2010, for a sample of Latin American countries.\footnote{I use the \emph{Montevideo-Oxford Latin American Economic History Data Base}  (\href{http://moxlad-staging.herokuapp.com/home/en?}{MOxLAD}), specifically the \emph{agriculture value-added} and \emph{manufacturing value-added} variables. The former measures ``the output of the sector net of intermediate inputs and includes the cultivation of crops, livestock production, hunting, forestry and fishing.'' The later  ``[r]eports the output of the sector net of intermediate inputs.'' Both of them are expressed in local currency at 1970 constant prices. Finally, ``the depreciation of reproducible assets or depletion/degradation of natural resources were not deducted.'' Details about this dataset are presented in the data \hyperref[data]{section}. The plot also shows a vertical line which indicates when the income tax law was passed (author's data based on several reports and official information). I elaborate on the income tax law in the next \hyperref[tax:expr:ind]{section}.} Contrary to \citet[241]{Bulmer-Thomas2003}, I do \emph{not} find that ``[e]verywhere [...]  industrial growth exceeded agricultural growth.'' The extent to which the agricultural sector was contested is proxied by these sectoral outputs. Economic contestation implied both political and military contestation. Superior economic conditions can relatively easily be translated into better military capacities, which makes it easier for the advantaged group to impose its political agenda in a monopolistic way.\footnote{\citet{Boix:2015aa}.} The literature is consistent in agreeing that more political contestation leads to better conditions of state-building. For example, \citet[481]{Kurtz2009} argues that where ``no faction can easily become permanently dominant,'' state capacities should be stronger. Similarly, \citet{Geddes1991} argues that competition between two rival parties of about the same size creates clearer incentives to invest in political institutions. \citet[40]{Cardenas2010}, in his formal and empirical models, also finds that the ``concentration of political and economic power reduces the incentives to invest in state capacity.''\footnote{However, he models inequality between \emph{elites} and \emph{citizens}. I expand on this idea by modeling the period \emph{before} full democratization existed and also by modeling inter-elite conflicts.} 



