% (3) agricultural incumbents taxed or expropriated industrial output // logic behind each strategy
\subsection{Taxation and Expropriation\label{tax:expr:ind}}


% Explain both strategies
The historical evidence suggests that decelerated international markets put heavy fiscal pressures on Latin American agricultural elites to sustain the economy. As \citet[148]{Gallo:1991kx} explains, ``the economic crisis of the 1930s forced forced most Latin American states to shift their sources of revenue from export-based to domestic economic activities.'' Building on the idea of the ``stationary bandit''\footnote{\citet[]{Olson:2000aa}.} I argue that the agricultural political incumbents faced this economic downturn either by \emph{taxing} or \emph{expropriating} the industrial sector. Each strategy represented a best response depending on the rate of industrial growth in a country. Crucially, industrial elites accepted taxation \emph{in exchange for tariffs oriented to protect the industrial sector}, producing a general economic boost which helped these countries navigate the economic crisis. 
 

% Expropriation
\emph{Expropriation} was the best response when the rate of industrial growth was slow. When industries grew slowly, the long-term benefits of having a secured, \emph{but excessively small}, source of tax revenue \emph{did not} offset the benefits associated with having \emph{immediate} monetary resources that came with expropriation. Expropriation brought immediate liquidity (fast access to money) in the short run, but it exhausted the industrial output in the long run. That is, when industrial growth was slow, immediate liquidity became more attractive, even when these resources got exhausted in the long run. Moreover, since industrial human capital and agricultural human capital are not equivalent,\footnote{For example, \emph{knowledge} to produce machines used to make glass can't be used to develop new agricultural \emph{techniques} to grow potatoes.} simply expelling the industrial elites and taking over the industries was not an efficient strategy, as it endangered industrial output in the long run. In other words, since landowners did not know how to run industries, they were better off  appropriating the surplus rather than taking over the industries\footnote{Presumably, there could be in the \emph{long run} technology diffusion between the two elites. I assume this strategy to be costly relative to expropriation in the \emph{short run}.}. This is a stylized theory. In reality, elites tended to engage not only in expropriation but also in nationalization and forced loaning. 

% Taxation
\emph{Taxation} was the best response when the rate of industrial growth was fast. 
Imposing a tax allowed agricultural incumbents to ``rob'' industrial output small ``doses'' at a time, without exhausting or precluding industrial development. From a strategic perspective, a healthy industrial sector became more attractive for what it had to offer in the future rather than the present. Hence, faster industrial growth shifted the focal point from the short to the long run. In these cases, it was in the agricultural sector's interest to protect and encourage the development of the industrial sector to secure even higher taxes. Hence, industrial tariffs were implemented to protect this sector, playing a very important role in the subsequent industrial development. Institutionally, the political elites had to be able to closely monitor industrial magnates and their personal incomes. Hence, an \emph{income tax} was implemented. This idea is consistent with the notion that political elites generally are better able to impose/raise taxes during economic booms. For example, \citet[647]{Campbell1994} explain that ``economic development should be directly related to individual and corporate income tax rates,'' while  \citet[59]{Besley:2011aa} argue that ``investing in fiscal capacity becomes more attractive [...] when wages or incomes [...] are higher.''


% (4) protectionism, representation and institutional investments
\subsection{Income Taxation and Institutional Investments}


% Taxation Levels and State Capacities
Income taxation was a state-building institution because it triggered the implementation of other state institutions. This paper identifies two such critical institutions, political competition within the elite and bureaucratic consolidation. Both were product of an inter-elite bargaining.\footnote{Though the public economics literature focuses predominantly on tax revenues, higher revenues do not mean higher stateness levels. For example, since American institutions were deliberately designed to limit the exercise of state power, the U.S. taxes very little (\citet[6]{Fukuyama:2004nr}). However, it is not reasonable to say that the U.S. has a ``weak state." Here the focus is on the \emph{politics} of taxation (see for an example \citet[]{Focanti2013}).} The tipping point that gave way to these inter-sectoral agreements was the unstable situation that was produced when there existed inter-elite political \emph{in}equality and economic \emph{equality}. That is, when both the industrial and agricultural sectors were about the same size (and hence, had the same military capabilities), but when only the latter had access to political power, i.e. \emph{state} power. Under these circumstances, neither sector had incentives to stay in its respective \emph{status quo}: the industrial class did not want to be taxed without receiving something in return, while the agricultural sector did not want to let pass a chance to capture industrial resources which would allow it to navigate the economic downturn in better conditions. Given the relative similar economic sizes and military capabilities, inter-sectoral war was not an optimal solution, motivating instead a political agreement.


