\subsection{Robustness Checks}

Cox \emph{proportional} models rest on the assumption that hazard rates are \emph{proportional} to time dynamics.\footnote{\citet{Box-Steffensmeier2004}.} Non-proportional hazard models are becoming an increasing problem across all subfields in political science.\footnote{\citet{Licht2011}.} In this section, I test whether this assumption holds. Non-significant p-values indicate that the proportionality assumption holds. Also, \autoref{fig:coxassump} shows that the spline fitted lines are constant across time. Each of the seven dots represents the regression coefficients of the seven countries in the sample.\footnote{This is for our main model, column 2 in \autoref{results:1}.} All in all, steady splines confirm that the hazard rates are, in fact, \emph{proportional}.


